MEV on Solana

@jito_sol is paving the way here with a Solana Validator that solves two key items:

- Open MEV market to distribute profits to validators

- Reduces spam (filtering and can send tips to validators which bots can't do)

Spam has seriously impacted Solana https://t.co/vJLOi7TmfQ

Suave by Flashbots for Ethereum

Suave is an app chain that unbundles the mempool and builder role for blockchains.

It aggregates transactions and preferences, allowing executors to compete to give users the best execution (with Users/interfaces getting a % of MEV back). https://t.co/agxOdhu7dS

MEV (Ethereum)

Pretty interesting that the authors surface that encouraging home staking actually made ETH less censorship resistant.

In PoW, miners would run MEV-GETH to get bundles with txs from their local mempool (i.e., non OFAC txs).

In PoS, this changed

@CelestiaOrg's Mainnet is launching ~2Q23 - a modular blockchain network.

Projects include:

- Astria (settlement layer that executes fraud/validity proofs for execution rollups)
- Eclipse (custom rollups using the SolanaVM)
- Dymension (settlement layer, a Cosmos app chain)

EIP4844 for Rollups:

This reduces the cost to post data on Ethereum (80% of the cost is posting). The posted data doesn't have to exist forever since L2 rollbacks can only happen within the fraud proof window.

Cheaper = Scale https://t.co/qJ1N5XPmTt

Mainstream UX: Stripe-to-Fiat crypto integrations with 11/16 partners on Solana

Base Upgrades:

1. QUIC (fast comms between RPC nodes and leader)
2. Stake Weighted PoS (Nodes can transmit packets based on stake vs FIFO)
3. Isolated fee markets per use case (very cool!)

@solana's Upgrade Roadmap

- @jito_sol: Validator filters spam and distributes MEV

- Firedancer: New independent validator client by @jump_ to reduce execution layer bugs leading to halts

- Openbook: A Serum fork (that may use SOL as its token). Needed to underpin DeFi.

(Continuing)

- New applications that are cross-chain native out of the gate:
@mars_protocol, @prime_protocol, @ComposableFin, and @rage_trade.

Mars and Prime offer cross-chain lending/borrowing, while Prime offers a similar use case leveraging @axelarcore for xc interop.

The authors are excited about Cross-Chain Apps

- Today most apps are silo'd on ETH. @chainlink and @LayerZero_Labs will allow deployments to work across chains.

- Cross chain apps offering more use cases (@THORChain's cross chains savings product and soon borrow/lend).

Ethereum - Cosmos Bridge

Historically, this is a very costly undertaking (see screenshot).

With ZK advances, though, a bridge between the two can make sense using consensus proofs (header computation off-chain, validity proof verified by Ethereum). https://t.co/kIlHKv9wY7

With $2.5B in Bridge Hacks alone estimated for 2022, we need a better model.

Types:

üåâ Externally Verified (least trustless; current model that relies on third parties like oracles)

üåâ Light Client Bridges: Underlying Chains validate

üåâ Rollup Bridges (most trustless).

Account Abstraction brings real programmability to transactions, a major UX boost. https://t.co/QucLgqHNv9

21/ Labs also points out they can be wrong, with a few things to watch for

- Growth in Mono chains over app chains
- Emergence of trustless bridges 
- Maturity of end-game tech, such as Zk-Rollups, Celestia, Fuel V2

20/ Labs believes there will be many specialized app chains at the base layer connected via trust-minimized bridges with a unified DeFi experience atop. 

Developers can customize, and users get the benefit of these specializations through a super app

https://t.co/nGOqF6G37P

19/ - Large community of Devs with multiple teams working independently on core development.
- Sub-second block times are feasible

18/ Why Cosmos

- Cosmos SDK makes it easy to deploy chains
- IBC allows for cross-state machine communication 
- IBC's trust assumptions are a big advantage
- Interchain accounts simplifies UX as you can control accounts on other chains

17/ Cross-shard communication makes it hard for labs to deploy here

- Avax: Similar to cosmos with a novel consensus mech, but relatively centralized and cross-subnet functionality and infra tooling are in the early stages.

16/ Sui/Aptos: Can offer high throughput/low latencies + move language is solid but early stage of tech/communities/TVL

- NEAR: Dynamic Sharding can be incredible with validators dynamically grouping txs based on stat analysis.
15/ Solana: Incredible community, progress, dev experience, and TVL. Will continue improving on tech to reduce outages + Jump creating a new client (firedancer) improves val diversity.

14/ - Polygon: Fast, great biz dev, high TVL and a lot of ZK work. Labs views the permissioned val set (and of bridge) as a risk. Should decentralize over time.

Other mono chains below, but mono focus conflicts with Labs' vision of a multi-chain future.
13/ - Polkadot: Labs views gov control over parachains as a risk. Adoption is early. Views work on XCMP (similar to IBC) as a unique advantage that took years of work.
12/ - Celestia: Tech not ready, also possible endgame - decoupling execution from data  and just offering ordering/DA at base layer offers security for rollups/app chains in a scalable manner

11/ - Ethereum L1: Too expensive

- Rollups: Centralized Sequencer and withdrawal times. Sequencer should decentralize over time

- Zk Rollups: Tech too immature, but a likley possible endgame

10/ The second half of the post goes into all the nitty-gritty of reviewing each L1 and L2 against the design requirements and labs needs. 

I'll attempt some quick TLDR summaries. All communities are AMAZING, this is just _specifically_ why Labs can't build on each one now. https://t.co/HUYUyKdcIg

9/ What are the platform requirements?

- Speed (close to CEX)
- Ecosystem (integrate DeFi apps beyond the limited scope of CEX apps)
- Decentralization (non-custodial, permissionless, and censorship-resistant)
- Cross chain-interoperable, tech maturity, and code portability

8/ TLDR labs believes (copy/paste incoming) 

1 - DeFi applications will be bundled into an integrated experience
2 - The world is increasingly multi-chain
3 - DeFi apps should deploy natively on multiple chains via outposts 

This outpost talk reminds me of interstellar ‚ú® https://t.co/7Y3tmOD5cz

7/ Interestingly, this leads to a world of both vertical and horizontal scaling

Vertical scaling since each app-chain can vertically integrate the outposts and primitives it needs to be successful 

Horizontally scaling since liquidity is coordinated between DeFi outposts https://t.co/MWJPbZBUuv

6/ This is critical for Labs' super-app vision. The team foresees a world in which the app layer is bundled (UI//UX) but the blockchain layer itself continues to fragment due to use cases that require varying customization at the base layer

5/ Labs is looking at a third option:

Application instances are deployed on multiple chains as outposts but are connected by leveraging a coordination layer that drives communication and liquidity allocation between outposts.

https://t.co/ms1yoU4w2S

4/ With many app chains, composability is key. There are two ways now 

- Standalone deployments on each chain that don't communicate (Uniswap on multiple chains) w each other

-  One unified chain (Thorchain), but this limits synchronous composability with apps on other chains

3/ There are drawbacks to not deploying on a monolithic chain 

- Composability, low social overhead coordination, and rapid prototyping at the app layer.

The main cost is synchronous composability. Labs argue this is only needed for a few apps (DeFi mainly) and there are fixes https://t.co/WRLWArvGWW

2/ Delphi Labs expects a world of specialized blockchains 

- Lower/Predictable Resource Costs
- Customizability
- Sovereignty 

Examples for each 

- Competing apps don't drive up TX fees
- Edit Consensus model, security, runtime, meme pool
- Not beholden to an L1's gov choices https://t.co/AcgmKNkbrq

12b/ Facebook also expressed support for competing app stores and Facebook devices would allow users to download apps directly from developers.

Unsure if Microsoft or Facebook will champion the Metaverse, but app stores flex/downloads is much better for metaverse devs vs Apple.

Microsoft has taken proactive measures

- Games Sold on PC Windows pay 12% fee vs 30%
- Non-Gaming apps can use their own billing solution
- Edge Browser updated to support cloud gaming streaming services 
- A commitment to support third party payment solutions and App Stores!

11/ Ball's Breakdown of the Metaverse

- The Metaverse: The overarching umbrella (The Internet)
- Metagalaxies: a Collection of virtual worlds under a single authority. Roblox is an example
- Virtual World: A single instance of destination (AdoptMe!)

12/ Recent Changes

10/ Change comes from Grassroots movements, those in the weeds

Microsoft got so many things wrong as the dominant player, take mobile:

- Missed winning form factor (touchscreen v Keyboard)
- Role of device (primary computing device)
- Appeal (everyone vs business)
- Price

9/ Sizing up The Potential 

Ball argues that if the Metaverse is 10% of Digital by 2032, and Digital's share of the world economy grows from 20 to 25% during that time and world economy grows by 2.5%, the Metaverse could be worth $3.65T.

8/ Regulation

Ball proposes that regulation could force Apple/Google or others to unbundle (OS, app stores, payments, related services) and have to compete in each area. 

This seems like an obvious headwind for traditional players and a tailwind for Metaverse options

7c/ The Crypto angle also offers much greater incentives for Developers (ownership upside is a given but no 30% fee and easier access to capital) and Users/Gamers (lend spare compute, bandwidth, reselling items etc)

Incentives drive the world

7b/ Ball describes how Crypto can offer a new alternative, where open systems win

Blockchain offers an incentivized coordination system to aggregate money, infrastructure, time and talent (I expanded this def) to compete with the traditional mega players

7/ Crypto Can Disrupt Traditional Platforms 

Platforms today have massive investments in services, tools, engineering talent, customer acquisition and content. 

These drive more users and developers and forces a lock-in on both - why closed systems (Apple) won.

6c/ Alternatives are still in their infancy, @urbit promises a world where users own all of their data locally (or have direct permission over it stored on the cloud) and developers can release whatever they'd like. @solanamobile has released an entirely new Web3 mobile stack.

6d/ Another Apple Example 

- WebGL is a JAvaScript API for complex 2D/3D rendering 
- Apple's browser only supports a subset of features
- Took Safari 4 years to adopt it 
- This pushed devs to the app store for apps
- App store brought high fees, and no interoperable metaverse

6c/ IMO it's hard to see the Metaverse thrive via Apple or Google Play Stores or on Apple devices 

The forced bundling of services, extractive fees (30%) and a closed system that doesn't afford developers the technical room to breath is a toxic building environment.

6b/ The discussion on Apple restricting innovation to drive users to its own Payment Rails is a wild one

TLDR Apple Blocked Browser gaming capabilities and drove users to Apps (where it could collect fees) - stifling innovation

Even Chrome is a repackaged Safari App ü§Ø https://t.co/olUWaoHoxg

6a/ App stores dictating Metaverse Monetization

"If a Call of Duty: Mobile user buys a $2 pair of virtual sneakers for her character, Apple collects $0.60. But if Activision asks the users to watch $2 worth of advertisements.. Apple collects $0"

Builders need more creative room

6/ OS and App Stores 

Apple/Google take a 30% cut on most App Stores Sales 

This is extremely high (most small/medium sized business have profit margins between 10-15%). 

Apple is making 2x just for providing the App Store.

5/ The Scale of Traditional Gaming 

- Jan 2022 Roblox averaging 4B+ Hours per Month (Up from 2.75B Y/Y)
- Jan 22' MAUs 226M (up from 76M Y/Y)
- In 22' Roblox R&D may reach $1B on an annualized basis
- Budgets of GTA:V and RDR2 cost $250M-$300M and $400M-$500M

4/ Sweeny's Law - @TimSweeneyEpic

"Improvements in local compute will continue to outpace improvements in network bandwidth, latency and reliability..."

This is in line with the Web3/Metaverse user doing "more" locally. This may shift more to the Edge vs Cloud

3a/ Latency Extended

A key issue is the Border Gateway Protocol (air traffic controller of TCP/IP) which serves data inexpensively and cheaply but this can lead to serious delays

The last mile also adds latency issues (i.e. @PollenMobile tackling 5G saves 20-40ms vs 4G)

3/ Latency 

Improving is crucial for real time experiences, but we fighting against the speed of light

NYC to Tokyo is 11KM, light commute takes 40ms or 10% better than the minimum for competitive video games

In practice its 230ms due to many reasons

1/ The Metaverse requires a lot of people all at once, but we are pretty far away from this.

There are countless examples @EveOnline is one (largest battle in history of 12,000 users overloaded the servers), Fortnite (100 players max) and Population one (Max 18 players).

Switching over to the games themselves, what is NOR building?

NOR is a platform for play

Developers build on NOR to create an expanding universe of gameplay. 

Developers bring their games, but remember the overall meta economy is run by the Aspects.

TLDR, @jon_charb put together an incredible post on the future of Ethereum on @Delphi_Digital 

The center of gravity being centralized block production (specialized), decentralized trustless block validation and censorship resistance. 

https://t.co/sFsoexaTMp

Pruning Data 

- EIP-4844 with monthly pruning 
- Weak Statelessness or state isn't req to val a block using witnesses.
- Huge SSD requirement for state disappears: a key bottleneck to scaling today
- State Expiry: Old state gets chopped from what builders need, can be reaccessed

Proto-danksharding (EIP-4844)

- Stepping stone to DS
- New blob carrying tx format that rollups use for data storage.
- Cheaper vs call data and pruned after a month to cut storage reqs.
- PDS requires nodes to fully download data, DS distributes storing/propagating between vals

PBS TLDR 

- Building blocks is complex and would lead to centralization. 
- By separating the builder and validator role, the validators can remain more simplistic and simply validate a block using data availability sampling 
- Validators decentralized

https://t.co/AHkyPwZbDN

PBS ‚Äì Proposer-builder Separation

- Builders will put together blocks and bid for proposers (validators) to select their block combatting MEV centralization
- Builders are specialized but validators remain decentralized 
- crList so builders are forced to include certain txs

Dank Sharding Continued 

- Much simpler and less complex vs previous sharding designs 
- Merged Fee market: One proposer that chooses all transactions and all data that go into a slot vs each sharding having distinct blocks and proposers 
- PBS (covered next)

Dank Sharding 

- Creates a unified settlement and Data Availability Layer
- Validators conduct DAS to confirm that all data is
available 
- A specialized builder creates one large block with the Beacon block and all shard data confirmed together.
- KZG so erasure coding is legit

Data sharding 1.0 isn't efficient

- Requires each shard's validator set to download the data
- very complicated, bad UX and a lot of attack vectors vs Dank Sharding 
- I.e. each of the 64 shards had sep proporosers and committees rotating from val set
- Fee market complexity

Mitigating MEV

- Flashbots allowing mom and pops to outsource block building
- Single Slot finality removes the threat of a reorg since 1/3 of vals required vs 1/32 attesting to each slot
- Single Secret Leader Election hiding proposer until it's their turn to prevent DDOS

/25 Closing

In closing, people's attention spans are shot so founder's optimize for TLDRs, captivating passionate stories, no surprise deal terms and thoughtful interactions. 

Founders, you are also interviewing. It's a two way street. Pick and incentivize the right daos/funds

/24 Tip 6)

Leave your audience with materials learn more on their own time (another reason for no 24 hour closes) and in their own learning style

Offer up a podcast or YouTube video you did, a white paper, tweet storms or medium posts.

/23 Tip 5)

No one wants a 30 min pitch on a 30 minute call 

You can tell people the meaning of life, they may tune out after 10 mins

Do a 5-10 minute pitch, then get everyone engaged. Answer questions. Get Into it. 

Be energetic, be passionate. If not why are you doing this?

/21 Tip 3) 

Keep the pitch deck to 10-15 slides 

If you can't convince sophisticated investors in an abbreviated manner, you won't be able to sell the world.

Point those interested to other more in depth materials, white-papers, podcasts to learn post call.

/20 Tip 2) 

Always be professional 

The space is small and you may end up working together on something at a later date. 

I once heard of a founder laughing at us for passing on a round, and I will likely never back them in the future.

/19 Housekeeping Tips üßπ

Tip 1)

Never dismiss an analyst or associate at a DAO/Fund. 

In next-gen funds, these people are specialists in certain areas and their opinions are well respected internally.

/18 On Tokenecon ü™ô

At the pre-seed/seed stage full token econ does not have to be fully fleshed out. 

The keys are the product, GTM, value prop, community and team. 

As long as a team didn't shotgun give away all of its tokens too early, optionality to optimize exists

/17 A key item is that stakeholders want to know what you have done in the last week and quarter. 

The space moves too fast to wait to build until a funding round closes. 

What technical work have you completed, where are you with your deligence? Share it.

/16 On The Tech Stack üë©‚Äçüíª

Teams should have strong reasoning for why they are building on a certain L1 or L2 beyond "they can give us money" and "the buzz is real"

Money is cheap and the buzz is short lived

If you're unsure and investigating that's fine, but be honest

/15 Team allocations matter immensely. 

Make sure you have enough not just for your current team, but a plan and buckets to incentivize the next phase of killer talent you need. 

The %'s can scale down as the project grows in $ terms, but plan for it.

/14 On Allocations üíµ

Be very thoughtful on your token cap table

Giving everyone an allo gives an allo to no one

Don't expect a fund/dao to do the work with a $25-$50k check

Make sure you are getting what you need from a DAO, fund or angel, and they have an actual stake

/13 Last on deal terms, know your exit. 

We are all building toward a community owned world where incentives allow anyone to build out a project and be rewarded 

If you mention an IPO on the phone, funds/DAOs will think you're calling in from 2002. 

An IPO rarely makes sense

/12 For example, @lex_node and @SH_Brennan do this everyday for @Delphi_Digital's port cos and potential port cos. 

Check out LexDAO's repo https://t.co/MbMf4y9lUF

A law firm whose name is 4 dead partners may not be the most cutting edge.

/11 On Legal Docs

Make sure you pick a law firm that's next gen/tech and can deliver on what's market for crypto. 

Ask your potential lead investors if they can help draft docs for you that your outside legal can then review (to ensure you are protected as founders too!)

/10 Vesting should align everyone at the virtual (thanks COVID) table and be realistic so stakeholders know the founding team won't irish exit

12-18 months vesting for a game that will take 5-10 years to deliver on - makes zero sense to everyone other than cash grab fans.

/9 On Deal Terms ‚úíÔ∏è

Don't surprise on the token valuation. If you're giving an equity valuation, tell them the percentage of tokens that equity entity is getting so the fund/dao can back into the real FDV

"Surprise! You're investing at 2x the val" - no one wants this at closing

/8 One last pet peeve on investors, never tell someone that a fund has committed or is leading if they haven't agreed to, and agreed to let this be known publicly. 

If you get caught in a lie, click - the fund/dao is now again mentally checked out.

/7 Remember to be very selective on your investors. Passive capital is likely NGMI in my opinion as money is cheap.

Chose DAO like focused funds where the owners and builders are one in the same.

https://t.co/kk3bZnZDco

/6 The salesly, "we are closing in 24 hours" has to be the dumbest move in the world. 

First, this gives no time for either side to build a thesis or conviction needed during bear markets 

Second, in reality the deal will take weeks to close. 

Give a realistic timeline ‚åõÔ∏è

/5 On Investors üí∞

Founders should have a reason to want a fund/DAO involved. They should have a clear idea on what specific value the fund/dao will bring their project and community

Founders you are interviewing funds too, it's a two way street. 

You are getting married üíç

/4 On Comps üó∫Ô∏è 

A team should have a clear understanding of any comps if they exist and their plans

Building in a vacuum comes off as ignorant if a founding team isn't aware a comp has a better strategy and is further ahead

Click - everyone has mentally checked out

/3 Stories Sell üìñ

They are memorable and your listeners can visualize your dream as you walk them from today, to a realized future

Great teams are great storytellers

If you can't tell you an engaging story, it's unlikely you will be able to convince the masses

/2 Before you build a deck remember that slides should be a TLDR. 

Your audience is a fund/DAO run by those with port cos, new deals, obligations and limited time. 

Instead, save the thoughtful deep answers for üìû's and telegram. 

Brevity is the soul of wit üîÆ

This ensures that fraud/val proofs can safely be generated by anyone

the result is that Celestia can maintain a global base of nodes on phones/laptops that are actually securing the network vs monolithic chains where only ever resource intensive full nodes can be deemed secure

But what if there was a way to make sure data is fully available without downloading all of it?

This is done by data avilability sampling. DAS sits at the core of Celestia (and ETH2.0)

By each node sampling a small size of data they collectively make sure all data is available

But these proofs can only be generated if rollup's data is known!

This is why rollups post all their compressed data to Ethereum. 

ETH full nodes download all compressed data of rollups to make sure no data is missing

Rollups are scalable since üöÄ

1) Data is compressed before posting to eth chain
2) rollups executing txs not ETH
3) multiple rollups can work in parallel

They are also scalable becuase they can be verified by fraud/validity proofs

On the legal side 

Sometimes the deal you think you‚Äôre doing is pretty different from the docs you‚Äôre supposed to sign

Take the time to review, negotiate and work together. 

If not, what you sign and what you think you have can be very different. 

If it‚Äôs too different, pass

On circle of competence 

No one wants to appear dumb in a world where everyone‚Äôs ultra smart in their silos

Relying on others means you don‚Äôt learn. Not doing the DD means you don‚Äôt really understand it. 

Take a few hours to learn it yourself, it‚Äôs worth it.

On FOMO, it‚Äôs usually the worst reason to invest 

You‚Äôre either too late and the FOMO is real, or you‚Äôre making a decision on hype or a relationship in place of actual DD and forming a thesis

Straight aping can work for a PA, not for multi year investments you have to know

Web3 Private deals are all the rage

We all know it will exist, no one knows what form

The risk to me is figuring out how value flows through the web3 stack and eventual liquidity given a lack of clarity on token fit in. 

That being said, we‚Äôre active + excited here

Also we‚Äôre all getting too comfortable with 1-2 year vesting for teams.

Most projects, especially games, won‚Äôt be delivered in 1-2 years. 

Teams need to vest with at least how long it takes to deliver the product. 

There has to be an incentive to actually deliver.

Raise less, at a lower val from funds and builders that will actually help you. 

Better R/R for them and less dilution for team assuming you have enough funding here to get you to the next stage.

Then go raise a larger round (yay traction) or forgo it alltogether

As liquid markets remain shaky/tbd the market‚Äôs appetite to fund private projects with $100M+ Val‚Äôs (not equity, but for the token) that are pre-product and/or with limited traction will fade 

Too much risk for much less upside, especially in light of an ok market

- The base layer only guarantees avail of messages (no execution)
- Txs are executed by applications (scalable since you only execute what you need not every apps txs)
- Node growth = more throughput given DA sampling is sublinear vs block size

14/ Helium's 5G rollout has already begun. I've received my 5G modem and small cell node and will be setting it up this weekend. https://t.co/Vl6OBy8mP3

13/ Helium is an important piece of infrastructure for the Web3 space - it offers the potential of a global 5G/IoT network that is community owned. 

With this potential comes risks and a lot of game theory to consider between Helium and wireless/wireline companies.
12/ üí≠ A partnership with a wireless company would be great but we don‚Äôt think Helium needs a partnership to be successful in 5G.
11/ üí≠ Wireless companies partnering with Helium makes the most sense since Helium can leverage untapped spectrum of wireless co‚Äôs and they get access in the home.
10/ üí≠ Cable/wirelines can compete (adds CBRS spectrum to WiFI boxes) which leads Wireless co's to partner with Helium for in-home access

9/ We also share mitigants for each

The game theory is interesting:

üí≠ We think cable companies are unlikely to partner with Helium (since then they are providing a 5G network wireless companies can roam on)

8/ üü° ISPs turning off broadband access to those running 5G nodes
üü° Congestion in the CBRS band that is publicly available (80MHZ of the 150MHZ in the band)
üü° Competition from cable/wireline providers (adding CBRS 5G antennas to your WIFI modem and competing with Helium)

7/ Helium is graduating from a wireless startup to competing on the global 5G playing field. With this large potential comes risks and hurdles to solve. 

Within the post we detail what we view as the largest hurdles to overcome. Below are a few of the major ones

6/ The U.S. carriers spent $150B on spectrum over the last ten years. 

Helium's 5G network will initially leverage free spectrum called the CBRS band, spending $0. 

The project can expand and potentially partner with carriers who have unused licensed spectrum too, such as @dish

5/ Also, 5G nodes sit on rooftops and on utility equipment where it is far from the end user (Inside a home/business).

Helium offers a solution since those running nodes (already 500k) have access within the buildings and homes where 5G is needed most. https://t.co/2WMSOu31pj
4/ Historically 5G was a challenge since the spectrum to support these promises doesn't travel very far nor does it do well in adverse weather or through foliage, etc.

3/ Helium is expanding to 5G, you see it in the news but it is a collection of wireless technologies to enable very high speeds (1Gbps) wirelessly, with very low latency and the ability to support a lot of devices.

2/ Helium's model made sense years ago since the project was completely inverting the traditional wireless

üì° $0 spent on spectrum by using free, semi-licensed spectrum 
üóº$0 paid to tower companies since nodes are inside people's homes
üí∞$0 capex since users purchase nodes

1/ Excited to drop a report on @helium with @tbr90 üì°

Helium has successfully bootstrapped an IoT network near ~500k nodes and the next era is 5G.

Why? Simple - crypto is community-driven and large funds that don't adapt won't be able to compete with the community at large. 5 people around a VC investment committee can't compete with the millions of minds globally.

33/ I am a believer that "eventually" all funds will seek to be on-chain clubs and more DAO-like in the future with easier access to buy in/redeem and the ability to effectively reward people for their specific work (sourcing, port co-work, etc) or value add (ops, legal,‚Ä¶
32/ 3(c)(7) - requires that all LPs be qualified purchasers (i.e., have $5M+ in assets, which  is at odds with global entry for a DAO)

31/ A typical DAO (large # of members, lack of KYC, etc.) would not be able to comply with the registration requirements and it's not clear that even a smart-contract-based traditional fund would be able to either.

30/ For an investment DAO, the reasons why these exemptions don‚Äôt work are

3(c)(1) - Works if you have 100 or fewer LPs (that‚Äôs an issue) and do not make a public offering of your partnership interests.

29/ Funds want to use these exemptions so that they can avoid ongoing disclosure, requirements around director activities, prohibitions on affiliated transactions, and trading activities such as short sales and derivatives trading. See more below.

https://t.co/KwWPbedSR9

28/ ‚Ä¶multiple people would count toward that total). You could also try for a 3(c)(7) exemption, but that is for ‚Äúqualified purchasers‚Äù (the test is you are an institutional investor and/or much wealthier than an accredited investor)

27/ Funds that do not take on passive capital usually rely on a 3(c)(1) exemption from the Investment Company Act, which entails not having more than 100 persons beneficially own a stake in the fund (this would involve a look through where an entity formed to invest and held by‚Ä¶

26/ Second) 

Outside of investment advisor exemptions, funds need to also comply with investment company registration requirements or filing with the SEC. Most funds use 3(c)(1) or 3(c)(7).

25/ ‚Äú A 2017 study by the National Venture Capital Association estimated the annual compliance costs for ERAs to be around $60,000 versus $330,000 for RIAs.‚Äù

https://t.co/vlxtPiIB6W.

24/ I'd need 100 tweets to cover it all, but basically, the number of legal restrictions, operations requirements, and reporting are insurmountable for a decentralized fund to comply with. 

Here‚Äôs a quick data point on the cost difference (doesn't include all of the headaches)

23/ Also, since most imagine crypto assets will be classified as securities, the VC exemption is just kicking the can down the road

If a fund becomes large enough and exemptions no longer work, they have to become a Registered Investment Advisor.

22/ Remember, if a DAO wanted to use one of these exemptions, that does not preclude them from complying with all of the rules still (KYC/AML, formation of GP and I-advisor entities, limitations on leverage, and redemption rights, and a laundry list of other items).
21/ Most crypto VC funds can not meet these requirements to be able to be an ERA (Exempt reporting advisor) and have to register right away with the government.

20/ First) 

VC funds that take on capital in the U.S. have to register with the SEC as investment advisors unless they meet certain exemptions private advisor (under $150m in assets) or VC exemption (20%+ of investments cant be in non-qualifying assets - aka not securities)

19/ Why don't funds just open the doors and let anyone invest or redeem as they please in an open, web3 investment DAO structure? 

The TLDR is regulations (in the U.S.) makes it extremely hard to run a compliant and permissionless investment DAO.

18/ Currently, I view this as an internal process of expanding inclusion and incentives for sourcing and portfolio company work, where all members of the fund are active and there are no roles for passive investors.

17/ Regardless, perfection is a moving target and I think the best Web3 VCs will change a lot in the coming years, a few predictions below

First, these VC funds will become even more DAO-like!

16/ In W3, VCs are stakeholders, just like everyone else, but let‚Äôs not forget that now their LPs can take active roles in supported projects too. W2 VC Fund LPs can't go onto Uber's discussion board and propose massive changes.

https://t.co/pI9TvU4RxB
15/ These activities range from thinking through token econ and incentives, future products or use cases, active governance discussions, evangelizing a project, and much more.
14/ But in W3, to remain competitive, VCs also have to be active day-to-day members within a community, full stop.

13/ Back to VCs - In W2 + W3,  they have to provide all of the original value adds 

Including legal help (formation, deal docs), ops, hiring and talent retention, and all the way to being a therapist or long calls to chat about direction, vision, and solving internal conflicts
12/ Ownership and the power to change in Web3 is earlier and open to everyone, respectively, vs Web2

11/ W3 stakeholders (which may be capital allocators or retail) are way better off since

- Earlier ownership (revolutionary) and incentives vs buying stock post IPO 
- Anyone can propose changes on a governance forum, vs Web 2 VCs which have unique access to a company's board

10/ In Web2, users don't even have access to vote with their wallet since they can only buy a stock at ridiculous valuations post IPO. 

Crypto stakeholders today get airdrops, can yield farm, and can take part in projects for ownership much, much earlier.

9/ In W3 apps (not L1s), the execution of changes may be semi-centralized today (multi-sigs, access to code, etc), but a community actually controls a project since they can vote with their wallets (sell the asset or gov votes) and their voices (discussions).

8/ In well-structured projects, a VC doesn't control the direction of a project, the community does. A W3 VC can post a governance proposal, or an engaged college student in Mumbai can post their thoughts, both will be vetted by the community and valued on merit.
7/ Each project lives and dies based on its community. If a project isn't listening or adapting to its community (community = users and owners are the same) then usage and capital flows away.
6/ Jack views VCs as controlling entities for projects, but this depends on the VC and the particular investment structure used. At its best, the space is a meritocracy and entirely community-driven.
5/ Those VCs that are just capital allocators will get weeded out as time goes on since money is cheap and founders are looking for stakeholders to be dedicated community members.
4/ In W3, capital allocators and community members should be one and the same; there should be no dichotomy.

Huge shoutout to @ZeMariaMacedo @lukedelphi @lex_node @YanLiberman and to the entire Delphi Labs team for their work on Mars as contributors

The goal of The Mars Risk Framework is to ensure the safety of the protocol but to also codify the addition of assets so the process does not lead to a political situation where assets are added based on their hype vs the specific risk parameters that should be in place.

From here a scorecard is created which leads to a final numeric score for each asset.

With a score, risk parameters (below) can be set

üî¥ Optimal utilization
üî¥ Exposure limit
üî¥Collateral types
üî¥ Kp (responsiveness to the market to changes in the interest rate)

Each asset is scored for each risk category using metrics such as volatility and volume (market risk), time since launch and audits (Smart contract risk) and team and centralization (counterparty risk). This is not an exhaustive list

The Risk framework involves assessing three main categories

üî¥ Market Risk: Measures the liquidity and volatility of the asset.
üî¥ Smart Contract Risk: Measures the riskiness of the asset at the technical layer.
üî¥ Counterparty Risk: Measures the centralization risk of the asset https://t.co/J8lmCx4Hr4

Central to Mars is its Risk Framework

In other words, figuring out the riskiness of assets on the platform and setting risk parameters for those assets in a non-political and methodical way to ensure the sustainability of Mars.
In total 2.5% of MARS is earmarked for lockdrop participants, with more going to those who are more long-term aligned with the protocol given the boost on longer lockup periods.

UST lenders will earn xMars too

These UST lenders will also receive xMars as well which accrue on a per-block basis during the locked time.

Mars will be released as a lockdrop

üî¥ Lock UST
üî¥ Longer you lock for (up to 52 weeks) = more weight
üî¥ 14 days to decide, last 2 locked to prevent whale games
üî¥ Claim MARS upfront as lenders
üî¥ UST locked goes to use in the protocol - aka can be borrowed by users https://t.co/0XI6oNJsYc

Ultimate token distribution is very important (method moreso, next tweet)

üî¥ 55% community
üî¥ 20% team
üî¥ 10% reserve
üî¥ 10% investors
üî¥ 5% airdrop https://t.co/OXuPnw2uSg

Shortfall events (different from illiquidity events where utilization rates are at or near 100% and lenders can't withdraw) are backstopped by a UST insurance fund, xMars staking pool and printing Mars, in that order.

20% of fees go to treasury, insurance fund and xMars stakers

Shifting to token econ, Mars can be staked for xMars which is equal to one unit of voting power. This gives the power to participate in governance (risk parameters, asset listings, treasury spend and more).

xMars holders receive a share of interest rate revenue

If you set it to 69 degrees and it's 71 degrees inside, it will softly correct.

If for some reason it becomes 100 degrees in your house, the air conditioning will go into full fan speed at the lowest temperature to course correct. This is my understanding at least.

Mars uses a galaxy brain approach known as a PID controller for rates.

TLDR, the protocol is always calculating the difference between the desired utilization and actual utilization and continuously corrects.

Think about the air conditioning in your house. https://t.co/DMMHRNK2AP

If users can earn an extremely high APR farming, the APR on a money market usually only hits an interest rate well below this yield so there is a mismatch given borrowers have less of a reason to pay back debts and the yield delta means depositors have less of a reason to supply

On Mars, you can lend and borrow assets in a more efficient way due to a dynamic interest rate model based on control theory.

Interest rate models are usually linear or with a second slope for high utilization or curved. None of these react well to external market conditions https://t.co/7QnNqwPzjA

This isn‚Äôt about running off to an island and dipping on responsibilities üèù

It‚Äôs about realizing who can thrive doing part of what a founder does better, in a full time role

Every founder reaches a point where getting to the next level means firing themselves partially as they delegate to others or decentralize to the community 

Most won‚Äôt = ego 

Those who start to fire themselves win since they lean into the knowledge and time of others

On calls look for teams that promote each other instead of just themselves  

Pronouns: Those who use ‚Äúwe‚Äù or ‚Äúour team‚Äù is building this vs ‚Äúwhat I have done‚Äù 

Projects take a village, and there is a graveyard a galaxy long on founders who though they could do it alone

Also, each founders‚Äô mutual respect and understanding of each other leads to a better quality of life since instead of policing each other they let each other be free to explore the growth ops they can crush 

TLDR, Bullish high EQ, low ego teams with strong mutual respect

When I‚Äôm looking into a project I always look for camaraderie between founders and if they handle disagreements respectfully 

There are exceptions if someone isn‚Äôt a fit or they have a different vision, but there are ways to share in the growth prospects of spin offs

The most important thing for a project is the internal talent staying together. 

Empires fall from within and ego growth is usually the first crack

Maintaining trust and mutual respect internally can take a project from a budding idea to a limitless empire üè∞

10) The membership models favors a long term community. No surprise drops or rush to act, you can build and be engaged for the long term as an artist, collector or as an interested party

9) There are always risks. This is an early-stage community up against other strong communities. Also if the NFT space cools, artists aren't attracted or memberships get too high it could box out new members. Anyone can buy any dropped NFTs on the secondary market, prices vary.

8) https://t.co/X8Gxu0qEOm is relatively new but the team has already built out core features such as rarity trackers on-site and a membership scanner to see if the membership you are buying has unminted NFTs of past drops.

5) Release

Buzz sells. People want in on the VIP club with the line around the block. 

Make it mysterious and VIP to begin with, but make sure you open the project to the world.

Lean into mercenary capital. Not everyone's here for the tech, you may as well capitalize https://t.co/svb5PckdYv

4b)Tokenecon

Making sure incentives (yield farming rewards) go to the correct parties is crucial to attracting those who will help advance a project forward. 

Make sure your treasury is active, not idle, the team is locked up, and rewards are flexible to incentive growth areas https://t.co/gZXoaGIobH

4) Token econ

Value creation doesn't equal value capture. Make sure a token is absolutely critical to a project and currently (or will) capture value in the future

UNI, RUNE, SUSHI all capture value

MKR and GNO capture little value https://t.co/x1YqdshjcC

3) Community

People want an inclusive feel where the team takes their feedback seriously

Magical products drive a community as you want to attract the smartest builders/finance people in the space to iterate on your magic product

Solid communities grow like compound interest. https://t.co/qPWlWcByDB

2) Products

You can't get ahead by solely copy/pasting a competitor.

Focus on projects shipping new code that drive new and magical experiences. A Project should be continually shipping as standing still = death. 

PMF or some semblance of it is required. https://t.co/gYI6E2PhOa

1) Founders

You want founders that are charismatic (can tell a viral narrative) and technical (out-build the competition)

A dictator doesn't have all the answers. Look for founders who aim to fire themselves as they decentralize to the community who can grow a project faster https://t.co/29dFCsAc6S

Disclosure. I am long YFI and Delphi Ventures is long YFI.

Last, this is all moving incredibly fast and I can be totally wrong.

I think all of these projects will do well, and these partnerships will enable DeFi to offer wild new apps and use cases. 

I am being very specific that I think all projects will do fine, I just prefer YFI.

There will come a day when Yearn is unbundled. That's when you want to be on the lookout for buying subcomponent tokens. When a component becomes more attractive than Yearn. 

I.e. you want to go long AWS vs Amazon, or buy the internet piece of the cable triple play.

On the flip side, these "acq" governance tokens may offer asymmetric opportunities given their low market caps plugging into a beast. I would be on the lookout, but I think owning YFI offers a better R/R since the acq gov tokens have multi-faceted risk.
I believe large traditional investors will enter the space and look at YFI as both the go-to DeFi blue-chip and as a DeFi index or proxy given it's DeFi ecosystem.

Why I would rather own YFI 

- YFI captures value as these projects help build outs its ecosystem

- Value cap to "acq" gov tokens is TBD, not clear over the long term, and Yearn isn't married to them. If they aren't used or swapped out for better tech later, even worse.

Take it to the extreme - Yearn is getting exclusive access to build out its ecosystem with these projects, without paying a cent, just any value that would flow to these partnerships' governance tokens. Strategists would have used these projects anyway.

Value accrual to any of these "acquired" tokens is not guaranteed, and far from set in stone. Also Yearn is not married to these projects, it can merge with others later. You have to play devil's advocate. 

Value cap is clearer for the tighter partnerships - i.e. Sushi.

Net, Yearn went from yield farming these projects' tokens to $0 to "acquiring" them for $0 - and amazing feat. 

Imagine being able to purchase shares in Google's search biz or google docs instead of just Google. These "acquisitions" enable just that

Zooming out, I love how Yearn is moving the space forward. 

Smaller teams get Yearn's community, tools, developer mindshare, liquidity and the Yearn brand while Yearn gets exclusive access to these projects capabilities (swap, borrow/lend, insurance, strategies)

.@iearnfinance's mergers are fascinating 

- YFI is vertically (Cream, Sushi, Cover, Akropolis etc) AND horizontally merging (Pickle etc)

- Turning the entire investment banking model on its head (no exchange of tokens, swap or cash purchase. Also no 7% fees or road shows)

On the flip side, T-Mobile horizontally merged with Sprint and greatly expanded it's network (amortized this cost over a larger user base) and doubled down on competition (see $40, pay $40).

T-Mobile crushed its comps. (We were long $TMUS at Oppenheimer - Great call Tim Horan) https://t.co/qnZf8e6WY9

There are endless examples of vertical/horizontal integration. 

One I covered was the telcos purchasing content (T with Time Warner $85B, Verizon with Yahoo $5B). Old players vertically integrated buying the worst assets of a high growth area (media). They shoulda bought $NFLX https://t.co/KxwlOk3Skx

Another complication is what happens when active (YFI, Pickle etc) get so large they can't beat the market. Essentially they become the index provider.

Net, they prob attract more TVL than the pure-play index providers from crypto natives since they're here for the alpha "now"

This is also complicated by forking (UI, strategies, code, etc) but from what we've seen this is "much" easier said than done since you're not bringing the community (or TVL) with you which operates at light speed to improve foster the protocol. This can't be understated.

This is also complicated by the fact that a winning protocol (i.e. attracts the most TVL or users) may not have the best value capture

The good thing is if you win users/TVL you can "generally" fix the token econ later as long as its not destroyed from the get-go
- The active funds will take advantage of discrepancies/ARB throughout the aggregators, but also by arbing what the aggregators are investing in.

- Index + robo will plug into best alpha to juice returns (adding a nice cut and TVL)

At the end of the day Diamonds are valuable since the person receiving it (your partner) values it 

Bitcoin does this on a mega scale. Being valuable as money, not just a memento between partners 

/ End rant. Influenced by Explained on netflix

Net, $BTC makes better use of the playbook De Beers used to drive up the price of diamonds

Code/social consensus solve the centralized issues of De Beers and a global base of users/marketers help drive global adoption. BTC is cheaply verified + also lab diamonds is a red flag

6) Most of BTCs marketing is its price. 

Rally‚Äôs drive short term interest and long term price appreciation and longevity continues to attract mass appeal. It takes two seconds to check BTCs price, vs a while for diamonds

5) Defining value is tricky, but BTC one ups diamonds 

Diamonds have way less resale value (get 25% back) vs BTC which is very liquid. 

Diamonds have the (costly) 4C system for value, whereas for BTC you easily know through a transparent ledger your BTC is the same as another

4) De Beers ran with ‚Äú2 or 3 months salary‚Äù to purchase a diamond engagement ring

For BTC it‚Äôs vague, but the drive is to store ‚Äúsome‚Äù of your savings / holdings in BTC. 

If the finance industry broadly agrees on some % people should allocate to BTC, that‚Äôs obv bullish

3) De Beers created demand through savy marketing in movies, Ad campaigns and tag lines ‚Äúa diamond is forever‚Äù

Bitcoin is auto marketed by a global community through viral memes ‚Äústack sats‚Äù and strong value drivers (search for yield, uncensorable, SoV etc)

2) BTCs distribution isn‚Äôt limited, unlike the route De Beers took. 

I‚Äôd argue mass distribution helps BTCs positive feedback loop and drives global adoption, so I wouldn‚Äôt knock it

1) BTC‚Äôs supply is 21M enforced through code and social consensus 

De Beers controls supply artificially, but supply is not transparent and no one knows their true holdings

De Beers‚Äô playbook for Diamonds is directly comparable to $BTC, but bitcoins is enforced through code not a company

1) Control supply 

2) Limit distribution 

3) Create demand 

4) Link spending to success 

5) Define value 

6) Use price as marketing

Just trying to put the cloud + blockchain into perspective 

Outside of hard numbers, the large majority Of apps run on AWS Or Azure (more biz workloads)

Snapchat, E-mail, Video, Netflix, it‚Äôs all on the cloud. The cloud providers are behemoths

Flip side:

There are dozens of layer 2 projects being built to achieve scale without having to rely on a centralized party (AWS or party building solution on AWS) that may negate the need for the cloud + public blockchain

It all hinges on a viral, non custodian scaling method

The hybrid architecture of 

üî∏Cloud + Public Blockchain 

Makes way more sense than

üî∫Private blockchain + public blockchain

The former we‚Äôre using (cloud) speed/scale + (BC) immutability and user owned data

The latter is the former, but with more restrictions: if run on AWS

2) I think it‚Äôs naive to think crypto will replace the cloud

More likely dApps will leverage the cloud for storage and/or compute, where users hold the keys instead of the apps themselves or state is stored on a public chain

11/ Issues

üî∫Real token holder control
üî∫Allocation of treasury funds in real time
üî∫Fork and create new treasury. Hard not impossible.
üî∫Converting treasury to USD is an option, but adds token level sell pressure
üî∫Probably 100 more things

/Fin

10/ New Value Accrual Model

üî∏ $ZRX‚Äôs treasury proposal appears to be denominated in ETH. This could usher in a new way to value projects (I.e. how much of a base asset they are accruing times some multiple).
üî∫ Only works of the protocol is actually successful (TBD)

9/ Example

üî∏ $DCR is the easiest example I point to. 10% of block rewards go to a treasury, anyone can submit a proposal, anyone can vote. Just buy a ticket. Simple.

8/ Funding is vital

üî∫Projects need a model for decades long funding that is central to the protocol itself.

üî∏ Funding = path for long term evolution and upgrades by a global base of non-altruistic parties. One-off changes are NOT enough.

7/ Treasury aligns stakeholders

üî∏Those who own/build on the platform have an incentive to increase the value of the treasury and tokens, since they would be paid in them.

üî∏ Brings on non-altruistic builders who can also pay their bills.

6/ Instead

üî∏Submit a proposal to a treasury, and get paid in tokens. This removes the need to have to earn income on a project or service that is created.

üî∏No need to productize = less friction + potentially better apps.

5/ For Example

üî∏ @lightning / @Blockstream are doing phenomenal work on expanding $BTC's tech/capabilities. But they will eventually have to make money. 

üî∫Investors = realistic plan to earn money

4/ On-going protocol level funding removes the need to productize upgrades

üî∏For example, in $DCR, a developer can propose an upgrade and get paid in DCR. Same with $XTZ. 

üî∏This removes the need to productize services, which could add friction to the use case and development

3/ Treasuries = fork resistance

üî∏If you fork away, you lose the monetary value of the treasury

üî∏Treasury enables an outside party to propose changes that can be funded by the treasury, instead of their own pockets via a fork (only open to rich). Drives greater network effects
